lay in the biology of insects. Among the topics discussed are the control of molting, metamorphosis, reproduction, caste determination in social insects, diapause, migration, carbohydrate and lipid metabolism, diuresis, and behavior. The account features a summary of the most current and accurate thinking on the complex roles of ecdysone and juvenile hormone in the control of metamorphosis, a process still misunderstood and misrepresented in biological textbooks and many professional reviews. Throughout, the book's emphasis is on the biology of the organism and the ways in which physiological and developmental regulatory mechanisms are integrated into the insect's life cycle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aInsect hormones. 0aInsectsxDevelopment. 0aInsectsxPhysiology. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh  aAcetyl choline.  aAdenylate cyclase.  aAgeratum houstonianum.  aAglais urticae.  aAllometric constant.  aAnastrepa suspensa.  aAndrogenic hormone.  aApanteles congregatus.  aAraschnia levana.  aBaculovirus.  aBehavioral castes.  aBrain hormone.  aButterfly scales.  aByrsotria fumigata.  aCaffeine.  aCediopsylla simplex.  aCholecystokinin.  aChromatic adaptation.  aChromatophores.  aCocoon spinning.  aColeoptera.  aCritical daylength.  aCryptonephridial system.  aCuticulin.  aDacus.  aDevelopmental hormones.  aDevelopmental switches.  aDipetalogaster maximus.  aEcdysial membrane.  aEcdysial suture.  aEphemeroptera.  aExternal skeleton.  aFrontal ganglion.  aGlycogen.  aHabrobracon juglandis.  aHomeostasis.  aHormone assays.  aHypocerebral ganglion.  aInsecticyanin.  aJuvabione.  aKinoprene.  aLarval differentiation.  aLong-day insects.  aMagicicada.  aManduca quinquemaculata.  aMembracidae.  aMetabolism.  aM